items.name: StablyDiffused's Magnum Opus
items.description:
Licenses

Seek Art license, Dreamlike license

Introduction

So, this model has been in work for a very long time. This is not the same as my Aesthetic Mix, nor is it the same as my Wild Mix. It is a combination of the two with something extra thrown on top. It brought along a lot of the things that make the Aesthetic Mix and Wild Mix what they are, but it has some newer bits too. There are a lot of things this mix can do, and I feel like I've only scratched the surface so far. I look forward to seeing what you all create with it. I think version 1 still needs some work, but it is very good where it is at, and super easy to work with. So I figured I might as well release it in this state and let people use it while I continue searching for further improvements. As it stands right now, you get something that works well with a variety of prompts. It obeys prompts well and can produce a range of content. It is very consistent with the images it pumps out and has pretty decent anatomy.

Prompting

This mix is generally pretty easy to prompt. It works very well with any standard prompt you would use with my Aesthetic Mix or my Wild Mix. It can handle any prompt you'd typically throw at Protogen and probably a wide range of other prompts as well. It also supports some danbooru tags. Some of them get lost in the mix (it doesn't do any hardcore content well) but it is very capable with NSFW (softcore) or SFW content. It doesn't seem to lean heavily toward NSFW, but it does tend to lean heavily toward 3d render style generations. Put '3d' in your negative prompts to push it further towards realism if that's your intent. I recommend always putting 'masterpiece, best quality' in your prompt and 'worst quality, low quality' in your negative prompts. If you're looking for photorealism, I also recommend that you put 'photorealistic' in your prompt text.

Recipe

Below is a very long-winded explanation of what brought me to this release. TL;DR: This sh*t was a lot of f*cking work that almost never saw the light of day on multiple occasions. I pushed a lot of buttons, they pushed back, then I merged a lot of things, and came out with something I liked.

Initially this started off as an attempt to upgrade my Aesthetic Mix to use RPG v4 instead of v3. When I was done with that, I was not happy with the results. It didn't really bring much improvement to the Aesthetic mix. There was a little there, but nothing to write home about. So the recipe for that is as follows (this is important later on as it forms part of the base of the MagnumOpus mix but this recipe was never released.)

Aesthetic_v1.1: f222_v1 + elldrethSImagination_v10 @ 0.85
Aesthetic_v1.2: hassanBlend1512And_hassanBlend1512_1 + Aesthetic_v1.1 @ 0.85
Aesthetic_v2.7: Aesthetic_v1.2 + (rpg_v4 - v1.5-pruned-emaonly) @ 0.20
Aesthetic_v2.8: Aesthetic_v2.7 + (seek_art_mega_v1 - v1.5-pruned-emaonly) @ 0.25
Aesthetic_v2.9: Aesthetic_v2.8 + (modelshoot-1.0 - v1.5-pruned-emaonly) @ 0.15
Aesthetic_v3.0: Aesthetic_v2.9 + openjourney-v2-unpruned @ 0.05
Aesthetic_v3.1: Aesthetic_v3.0 + analog-diffusion-1.0 @ 0.05
Aesthetic_v3.2: Aesthetic_v3.1 + dreamlikePhotoRealV2 @ 0.10
Aesthetic_v3.3: Aesthetic_v3.2 + hasdx_hasedSdx @ 0.10
Aesthetic_v3.4: Aesthetic_v3.3 + (hassanBlend1512And_hassanBlend1512_1 - Aesthetic_v3.3) @ 0.15
Aesthetic_v3.5: Loaded into toolkit, pruned to fp16, and fixed CLIP.

After I rebuilt the Aesthetic Mix I was a little discouraged, but I figured why the hell not, let's merge it with the WildMix and see what happens. The result was actually something quite magical. It had all the aesthetics of the Aesthetic mix, and all the vivid colors of the wildmix. It was quite amazing and I liked it a lot, so I considered releasing it as an update to the Aesthetic mix, but then I discovered that all the NSFW content of the Aesthetic mix was neutered. It wasn't fully destroyed, just didn't work as well as it had before. It was super difficult to get an image of the subject with spread legs, the vaginas often came out with 1 or more extra lines, and nipple textures were mangled. I liked it, but... I didn't like it. For reference, the recipe for my Wild Mix is this:

ProtoDucHaitenMix_v5: Protogen 5.3 + (DucHaitenAIArt 2.0 - v1.5-pruned-emaonly5) @ 0.5
WildMix_v2.1: ProtoDucHaitenMix_v5 + (kenshi_10 - Anything-V3.0) @ 0.5
WildMix_v3: WildMix_v2.1 + SynthPunkSearch_raw @ 0.30
WildMix_v3.1: WildMix_v3 + vintedois-v1 @ 0.15
WildMix_v3.2: WildMix_v3.1 + (rpg_v4 - v1-5-pruned-emaonly) @ 0.20
WildMix_v3.3: WildMix_v3.2 + rfktrsDarkdream_v16 @ 0.1
WildMix_v3.4: WildMix_v3.3 + dreamlikePhotoRealV2 @ 0.1
WildMix_v3.5: Loaded into Toolkit pruned to FP16
WildMix_v3.5.1: Fixed CLIP positions
Baked in Standard 1.5 VAE

Then the subsequent mix, which I called Stably Diffused's Experimental Mix was this:

StablyDiffusedExperimentalMix_v1: WildMix_v3.5.1 + AestheticMix_v3.5 @ 0.50

So after that, I went on a journey. I was searching for a way to put better NSFW content into the new Experimental mix that I created. In the end I actually gave up... temporarily. Everything I tried either messed up the anatomy of the Experimental mix, or it didn't solve the issue at all.

So I moved on, thinking that I'll just work on something else for a little while and see where I get. I started working on an Animated mix that was going to be based off of grapefruit_v4 but pushing it more towards a semi-realistic 2.5d style without destroying the grapefruitiness of it. I got some results that were pretty good, but every time I made some success it still didn't keep the more hardcore aspects of grapefruit intact. It destroyed all of that. Again, on a whim I decided to merge one of these iterations with my Experimental mix just to see what happened, and again, I was pleasantly surprised. It still didn't retain the more hardcore aspects of grapefruit, but it did improve the NSFW abilities of the Experimental mix, and kept all the coolness that I saw in Experimental. The downside was that it also removed a lot of the realism that was in Experimental and it created something that was only about 2.75d. It was cool, but not cool enough. So then that started me off onto a new journey. I figured out something that would be able to fix the NSFW capability in Experimental mix, but I also wanted it to retain photorealism at its core. I had now learned how to use the Merge Block Weighted extension in Auto1111, and was playing around with it to find different ways to merge models. So that led to the following recipe to create a 2.5d Semi realistic Anime/NSFW base that had good anatomy, good eyes, and brought good aesthetics to the mix. You will probably notice that there are a lot of skipped numbers in the versions below. Those were the failures, we won't talk about those.

AnimeNSFWBase:

AnimatedNSFWBase_test_3: MergeBlockWeightedMerge::

Model A: Corneos 7th Heaven V2

Model B: Grapefruit_v4

Base Alpha: 0

Preset Weights: SMOOTHSTEP*2

AnimatedNSFWBase_test_4: MergeBlockWeightedMerge::

Model A: dantiondrawmix_20

Model B: AnimatedNSFWBase_test_3

Base Alpha: 0

Preset Weights: SMOOTHSTEP*2

AnimatedNSFWBase_test_5: MergeBlockWeightedMerge::

Model A: AnimatedNSFWBase_test_4

Model B: anidosmixV2_anidosmixV2

Base Alpha: 0

Preset Weights: SMOOTHSTEP*2

SR_AnimeNSFW:

SR_AnimeNSFW_v0.6: MergeBlockWeightedMerge::

Model B: AnimatedNSFWBase_test_5

Base Alpha: 0

Preset Weights: SMOOTHSTEP*2

SR_AnimeNSFW_v1.7: SR_AnimeNSFW_v1.6 + dreamlikePhotoRealV2 @ 0.15
SR_AnimeNSFW_v1.8 Prune to fp16 (fix broken clip)

Which leads us... finally... to what created the MagnumOpus mix v1:

MagnumOpus_v1.0: MergeBlockWeightedMerge::

Model B: SR_AnimeNSFW_v1.8

modelVersions.name: AnimeEdition-v1.0
modelVersions.description:
This is not an upgraded version, it is a supplemental addition to be used alongside the main model (or instead of if you don't want to use the photorealistic version). The main model tends to lean toward Photorealism, and this version is designed to lean towards animated and 2d.

This is the same ingredients as the main model, just with an extra merge at the end to push it into anime territory. The result is a model that has a similar aesthetic to the main model, but a lot less realistic and produces much more animated style content. It also is able to do NSFW content quite a bit better than the main model. It does best with danbooru tags when you're trying to get Anime style content, or NSFW content. Also, eyes will come out better if you have 'restore faces' turned OFF.

The model is already pruned to fp16 with the VAE baked in.

I'm aware that some of the terms in some of the example images are pointless (like including photorealistic, or putting anime in negatives...) I did this intentionally though so that I could re-use the exact same prompt from the main photorealistic version of this model so that you can see the difference between the two versions.

Model B: AnimatedNSFWBase_test_3

items.name: WhiteSpace
items.description:
WhiteSpace SD Model


It's called Whitespace, but it's not really whitespace at all. I was trying to add a more colorful and mysterious feel to the Pastelmix line of models.

Some prompts that work well with the models include the following.

"prism, glowing, glitter, particles, bloom, extra lights, cinematic lights, glowing white particles, +a"


There are three types of models (WhiteSpace Prism, Quasar, and Black), each with slightly different characteristics.

First of all, the Prism model is the base model for the other models and has the most stylish and distinctive look. It has a jewel-like design and unusual light effects. Recommended setting #1 is the best fit.

The Quasar model takes the Prism and mixes it with the Chilloutmix and Ultracolor models to create an unusual semi-photorealistic model. It's still an unusual color, but it's a bit more like the other semi-photorealistic models. This model can be a bit unstable. Recommended setting #2 works best.

The Black model was created by mixing Prism with a little bit of Helltaker lora, Maplestory lora, and World Flipper lora to create a bold and strong style. Enjoy the cartoon-like feel with strong lines and contrast. Recommended setting #2 works best.

A detailed comparison of each model is shown in the image below.
(WSB = Black, WSQ = Quasar, WSP = Prism)



Based on the stable diffusion WebUI, the recommended settings are:

Recommended setting #1 (oldQPrompt):

- Prompt: masterpiece, best quility, high_quality, high_resolution, masterpiece*portait,

- Negative prompt: lowres, bad anatomy, bad hands, text, error, missing fingers, extra digit, fewer digits, cropped, worst quality, low quality, normal quality, jpeg artifacts, signature, watermark, username, blurry, artist name, ugly, duplicate, morbid, mutilated, tranny, trans, transsexual, hermaphrodite, extra fingers, mutated hands, poorly drawn hands, poorly drawn face, mutation, deformed, ugly, blurry, bad anatomy, bad proportions, extra limbs, cloned face, disfigured. more than 2 nipples. ugly, extra limbs, bad anatomy, gross proportions, malformed limbs, missing arms, missing legs, extra arms, extra legs, mutated hands, fused fingers, too many fingers, long neck

- Sampler: DPM++ 2M Karras or DPM++ SDE Karras

- Upscaler (optional): 4x-UltraSharp

- CFG Scale : 6~7

-Sampling steps: 20

Recommended setting #2 (newQPrompt):

- Prompt: (finely detailed, distinct image, ultra resolution, extremely amazing detailed, awesome detailed), subsurface scattering, best ratio four finger and one thumb, masterpiece, best quility, high_quality,

- Negative prompts: lowers, (worst quality, low quality:1.4), EasyNegative, text,error, jpeg artifacts, signature, watermark, username, artist name

- Sampler: DPM++ 2M Karras or DPM++ SDE Karras (Black model shows good quality even with Euler a)

- Upscaler (optional): 4x-UltraSharp

- CFG Scale : 6~7

-Sampling steps: 20~26

These are the settings in my case and I don't see any problems not following them, but in my case the above settings have the highest quality.

You can use it with any model trained in 1.4 or 1.5, even 2.0 512x.

Merge of two LoRAs trained over basic SD1.4, on the same images and parameters with different amount of training steps. Averages to 30 steps/image over 90 training set images, half of them being crops of her face.

This improves over my previous tests by converging on the face more easily on 20 samples. It used to take 100 samples to converge. Also, back shots are hard because it always tries to portray her from the front, leading to bad anatomy.

items.description:
Riza Hawkeye Character LoRA

If you enjoy my models and want to support me you could buy me a coffee!

This LoRA mimics the character Riza Hawkeye from Fullmetal Alchemist. You can manipulate it in a few different ways:

pixel-Riza + long hair in negative prompt: standard look

pixel-Riza + long hair: Riza with her hair down

pixel-Riza-Back: gives an image of her back tattoo (might give different colored tattoo so I recommend adding "red tattoo" to your prompt

The example images were created with NeverEndingDream on 0.75 weight but feel free to experiment on your own. I tried briefly to mix it with a couple of different embeddings and it gave back decent results but you might find a better way to mix them (changing different weights etc.).

To change the weight just change the '1' in this prompt: <lora:riza-Hawkeye-LoRA:1>.

I'd love to see the art you guys make with it so feel free to add them in comments.

How to use LoRA's in auto1111:

  • Update webui (use git pull like here or redownload it)

  • Copy the file to stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora

  • Select your LoRA like in this video

  • Make sure to change the weight (by default it's :1 which is usually too high)

In this example, not only a good-looking Korean face is generated, but also a concept that usually can only be used in anime-style models like AbyssOrange is also used: Pillory This is the original intention of my creation of this model: to retain the pretty Korean style face without losing creativity. Let me first talk about why this model was created. As is known to all, the ChilloutMix model is a popular realistic model, but it is dependent on lora, and does not perform well without lora characters. In addition, due to the scarce of the training dataset, many tags are useless in CHilloutmix, many clothes, pendants, and poses cannot be displayed. So I thought, maybe it can be merged with some anime-style models to learn the tags of poses, clothes, etc. So this model was created, the painting style is between 2D and 3D.

Compared with chilloutMix, the advantage of this model is that it can produce better-looking pictures without relying on lora, and the 2.5D painting style is not easy to make the uncanny valley. (Of course, I suggest to use it with some beautiful loras) More importantly, it can match almost all tags freely, and it has learned the meaning of tags from other style, so that you can freely match various clothes, poses, toys, etc while chilloutmixe is hard to do.

Compared with the anime-style model, the model is more Korean-style and beautiful.

items.name: Lawlas's Yiffymix 2.0 (furry model)
items.description:
Disclaimer: Despite having "Yiffymix" in the name, the model itself has nothing to do with Yiffymix.

‚ñºAbout

Hello and welcome. This model is an upgrade from my previous model Lawlasmix. I used AOM3 and miscellaneous models during the making of the model, so don't forget to check that out.

It's capable of generating sfw/nsfw furry artworks in general with consistent quality, while having decent details in hands, clothing, background, etc. Compared with the old Lawlasmix, it's overall more anime style oriented, and doesn't need artist tags all the time (It can still change the styles if you use them anyways). It can be tricky to write prompts for the model if you're new to it, so make sure you read the tips carefully!

‚ñºTips

  • Personally I use it with these settings:

    Batch count: 6

    Clip skip: 1 or 2 (for different styles)

    CFG: 6-8

    steps: 40-150

    Size: 512 x 704 or 512 x 780 .etc (then use hiresfix, or SD upscale in img2img )

    Sampler: DPM++ 2M Karras or Euler a

  • Prompting

    The model can make amazing results with very simple prompts so long as you use it right. It uses both danbooru and e621 tags, like 1boy, 1girl, solo_focus. It's recommended to start the positive prompt with "(furry art, uploaded on e621:1.4)" and negative prompt with "(worst quality, low quality:1.4)". Since the merge has significant amont of anime models in it, you need to give more weight to furry related tags. Use tags like (anthro furry:1.6) in the positive prompts and (human:1.6) in order to get it to make furry art. The model performs rather well when you specify the color of the fur. For instance, (detailed red scales:1.5), (detailed blue fluffy fur:1.5). Feel free to check out the example images for their prompts to help you write your own.

  • VAE

    If you don't use any vae with the original version, the outputs of the model may suffer from loss of colors. As a result, consider using anythingv3 vae or orangemix vae. I provide the download of orangemix vae here. However, if you don't want to use any VAEs or can't get them to load, you can now choose the versions with a VAE baked in the model.

  • Embedding

    Feel free to use other textual inversions, but I strongly recommend boring_e621. It's trained specifically on furry artwork and works great in this case. Try EasyNegative as well

Known problem(s):

  1. Since the has AOM3 mixed in it, it's very common for it to generate results in which characters have "M" shaped hair. Consider using tags like (unique hairstyle, unique fringe, unique bangs:1.6) or using img2img to generate alternative images to help you get to the desired results.

  2. The model has reported to be temperamental so to speak. I suggest setting batch count to more than 2 so you have more results to choose from.

‚ñºCredits:

Here are models used as far as I can remember:

  1. AOM3

  2. DivineEleganceMix

  3. My previous model

I apologize for not keeping a record of the models I used. Without their amazing work, this model wouldn't have even existed. Kudos to every creator on this site!

items.description:
Making models is costing me my children's tuition. Do you like what I do? Feel free to buy me a coffee ü§óüíñ

This LoRA was made due to the request of an Anon Discord user and my appreciation for the art style of Silence Girl. I used NED (Never Ending Dream) as a base model for training. This LoRA was trained on about 90 Images of her art. I've been testing out some new things for style LoRA's so please let me know what you thinking by dropping a review. üíñ

It's flexible enough merge with Character LoRA's and other Style LoRA's aswell. Please check the examples.

The LoRA itself is quite flexible with various weights. I personally recommend using Anything V4.5 to generate images with this model as it captures the 2D art style better but in the end it's up to you to decide and test out what works best for you.

There isn't any trigger words that specially trigger the LoRA ( I still don't know how to do that ) but the LoRA works just fine at a weight of "0.9" or more/less but might require tuning based on the model you're using it on. Works great on Any V4.5 and with other Character/Style loras, or on any anime model out there.

(SMALL DISCLAIMER)

Using WD Vae might make it end up looking too oversaturated so I'd recommend using AnythingV3 or AnyV4 vae.

Please enjoy and consider supporting me.

How to use LoRA's in auto1111:

  • Update webui (use git pull like here or redownload it)

  • Copy the file to stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora

  • Select your LoRA like in this video

  • Make sure to change the weight according to the instructions (by default it's :1)
